         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>55, 115</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>368</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>39</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Thereupon the hunter [told] how he (went) to the forest, (how) he there hit the elephant, how immediately the elephant, to keep him alive,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>325</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Darauf [berichtete] der Jäger, wie (er) zum Walde (ging, wie) er dort den Elefanten traf, wie der Elefant (ihn) sofort, (um) ihn am Leben zu erhalten, (Verbarg, wie er dann selbst(?)) [sich] die Stoßzähne ausriss, ...</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Thereupon the hunter [told of] how (he went) to the forest, (how) he hit the elephant there, how the elephant, (in order to) keep him alive, immediately  (hid him, how he then) pulled out [his] (own(?)) tusks, ...</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>325, 368</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>233</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1952"/><citedRange>15-16</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>140</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(hid him, how then he himself) pulled out the tusks, or how, because of this, the earthquake, the raining of divine flowers [and]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2 #a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1969"/><citedRange>262</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2 #a3 #a4 #a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013"/><citedRange>164-165</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>215</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1988"/><citedRange>251</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>87</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the praising of the Bodhisattva (by) gods, (humans), ... happened, or how even Indra sat on his knees before the Bodhisattva. That, too, (he told (?)) to the queen</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>729</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Thereupon, presenting the tusks to the queen, he says: And these tusks (he commanded me) to give to you. Shedding tears</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(the queen speaks: What said (?)) the compassionate being? The hunter speaks: ... || In the S.-tune: || Not well (you did, when you sent the hunter)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>243</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1981"/><citedRange>488</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>106, 136</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:meunier2013"/><citedRange>177</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">to kill (me(?)). Repent! Drop the hate from [your] thoughts in all births and do not (let) the hate (?) ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Bereue, entlass den Hass aus [deinem] Denken in allen Geburten ...</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">... repent, discard hate from [your] thoughts in all incarnations ...</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>338</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the tusks I sent to you; take them, oh noble one, [and] forgive!. 1. When (Bhadrā) had heard this, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1 #b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>89</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Als [Bhadrā] das gehört hatte, ... lähmte (alle) ihre (Adern), sie wurde ohnmächtig [und] fiel zur Erde.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">When [Bhadrā] had heard this, ... paralysed (all) her (veins), she fainted [and] fell to the ground.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>124</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1969"/><citedRange>257</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... threatened (all) her (veins), she fainted [and] (fell) to the ground. Immediately king Brahmadatta let Śītābhāsa-pearls (be brought (?))</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>109</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>16</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>26</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>86</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(Thereupon) queen Bhadrā (, having come round again,) speaks, remembering [her] previous births, turning towards the mountainous region of the Himavant (and) thinking (?) (of her birth) as an elephant:</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1972"/><citedRange>469</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>38</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... reproaching herself: || In the H.-tune: || Oh! Ignorant and mean, because of hostility, jealousy and hatred,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4 #b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>732</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>187</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1966"/><citedRange>269</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1970"/><citedRange>259</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1976a"/><citedRange>77</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>139</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>87</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">not considering his (virtue), I have ordered to kill him. The one compassionate and in spirit [and] mind pure, like a wise man</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>28</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the followers with love. 1. Separated from him, they have (now) become unprotected [and] they will break asunder. I wonder where they will be going? Long</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Having been separated from him, they have now become miserable and will fall apart. Where will they go?  (cf 16)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>219</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice></p>
